prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Subset 1 (Brightest)
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
This proposal will observe the submillimeter continuum emission at 1.3 mm in cluster galaxies at z>1. The redshifted (rest-frame ~500um) optically thin dust emission is a measure of the total ISM mass of the galaxies, modulo assumption about dust properties and the dust to gas ratio. Comparisons of the ISM mass with other galaxy properties such as SFR and stellar mass will allow us to examine the star formation efficiencies and gas fractions in the extreme environments in clusters during an epoch of star formation and AGN activity in cluster galaxies.
This science goal contains the brightest sources in our sample, with a desired rms sensitivity designed to obtain at least a 5sigma detection.
There are two galaxies in this subset which can be observed in a single pointing (10.88_J143218.1+325315_61_J143216.5+325224_60).

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: The correlator set-up is choosen for submillimeter continuum observations, with a bandwidth of 7.5 GHz.

For our goal of targeted imaging of galaxies at z>1 in order to measure the global submillimeter continuum emission, we request an angular resolution of 1 arcsecond (configuration C36-2). This resolution is sufficient to prevent blending with nearby sources, but not so high that we will resolve our targets.
Configuration C36-2 is requested instead of a more compact configuration in order to mitigate shadowing.

Our requested rms is driven by the need to detect the submillimeter continuum emission at 1.3 mm in galaxies at z>1. The expected 1.3 mm flux is determined using far-infrared 100um observations from Herschel/PACS and appropriate galaxy templates. All of our sources in this science goal will be detected at >=5sigma given the expect 1.3 mm flux, providing a robust detection. In the case that our predicted 1.3 mm fluxes are overestimated, the science goals of this proposal can still be accomplished with >3sigma detections.

Our target sources are at high declination (+32 to +35) and so may suffer from shadowing. Our targets reach above 30 degrees in elevation for three hours per night, allowing for flexibility in scheduling the science blocks to mitigate shadowing as much as possible. The total proposal time is modest, only 8 hours.
These high declination observations are justified given the uniqueness of our sample. We propose to target galaxies in galaxy clusters at z>1 that have existing far-infrared observations, necessary for a robust measurement of their star formation, most of which is obscured by dust. Our cluster sample is uniformly selected and statistically significant, the only such sample at z>1 to have far-infrared observations. Observations with ALMA, due to the need for sensitivity and moderate resolution, are necessary to carry out this analysis in a statistical manner. Other facilities are not sensitive enough or suffer from low resolution (making counterpart identification challenging) to observe a large enough sample from which robust conclusions can be drawn.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Recent observations have uncovered an epoch of star formation (SF) and AGN activity in galaxy clusters at z=1-2, providing an unprecedented opportunity to examine galaxies in extreme environments prior to the passive evolution seen in local clusters. We propose to quantify the gas properties in 129 cluster galaxies during this pivotal epoch through submillimeter continuum emission. From this we will measure the total mass of the ISM and relate this quantity-which is dominated by molecular hydrogen in high redshift galaxies-to ongoing SF and AGN activity as a function of environment. Combined with our existing deep infrared observations and ancillary data, we can then derive the star formation efficiencies (SFE), thereby constraining the mode(s) of star formation in a statistical sample of active cluster galaxies. We will additionally quantify the gas fraction in cluster galaxies, providing a necessary complement to ongoing analyses in field galaxies. This modest 8 hour proposal will provide the first statistical sample of cluster galaxies with measured ISM properties at z>1, from which we will paint a clearer picture of the relationship between environment and galaxy evolution.
